Using R Packages
R and the open-source R packages installed1 on our SCE (Scientific Computing Environment; i.e. DaVinci) are validated and can be used to generate outputs for reporting. This means that any R package you can access with library without first installing it has been validated and can be safely used.

The version of R and associated set of packages are updated periodically as part of operational releases. The validation process obviates the need for double programming of the functionality of the package but users remain accountable for understanding the implementation of the methodology (e.g. solvers and defaults). You can learn more about validation here

How to use the validated R packages
There are two ways in which to load the installed packages on our SCE (i.e. DaVinci).

Validated R packages are pre-installed and can be loaded using
library(<package>)
The set of pre-installed packages are referred to as a bundle. When you select the version of R the most recent bundle will be selected. See here for more information on R bundle management.

Validated R packages are also hosted on the DaVinci instance of posit package manager which are aligned to the version of R being used and require users to install the package using
install.packages("<package>", repo = https://rspm.apps.dit-prdocp.novartis.net/validated-R-4.1.0/2023-11-10+MTI6MzYxMjs2RkMxRTZBMw, lib = "<local_path>")
Users should also select a repo snapshot via selecting a date in the setup tab to ensure reproducibility.

What if the R package (or specific version) you need for reporting is not already installed?
In this case, there are two options available to users with different time horizons and levels of user participation.

Option 1: Request a package as part of the SCE release cycle.
You can use the MELZI app to request your package. Note that the releases on our SCE take place with a frequency in the range of months and therefore the turnaround time can vary depending on the timing of the request with respect to the release cycle.


Option 2: Adhoc installation of a package for time-sensitive GxP activities
Note
You might encounter yourself in this situation if you need a package that is not on DaVinci, or you need a more recent version of package in DaVinci, and you can’t wait for the next DaVinci release

The process of adhoc validation of publicly available open source R packages is described in WP-8125598. The guidance here provides a specific example of how the work procedure may be implemented in practice, although it is not the only compliant way.

For the most common use case, in which the package originates from CRAN, the following code will install the package from a pre-specified posit package manager (PPM; previously RSPM) snapshot in go/rstudio.

Running the ad-hoc installation with brave
You can install the package that you need for GxP activities using the package brave which is available in DaVinci. brave is an internally developed package that apart from facilitating the adhoc installation of R packages, performs the packages’ risk assessment in a semi-automated manner and provides a Risk Assessment form.

The function of interest from brave is adhocRequire. It will install the package in a temporary folder. The usage of the function is as follows:

# Navigate to the path of R program that generates your output

# Set this location as your working directory
setwd("<path of R program that generates your output>")

# Load the brave package
library(brave)

# Set your repository snapshot date
ref = 'default'

# Execute the adhoc installation
brave::adhocRequire("<package>", ref=ref) 

You must first navigate to the folder that contains the programs that will use this package, and set it as your working directory with setwd().

Then, you must set your repository snapshot date and run the adhocRequire() function.

TipHow to choose the repository snapshot date
This is configured using the ref argument in the brave package. There are three different options:

ref = "recent": the Posit Package Manager snapshot 2 days prior to today’s date. Note this install may require dependencies that are not compatible / available with the current DaVinci release
ref="<YYYY-MM-DD>": the Posit Package Manager snapshot form an specific date. Note this install may also require dependencies that are not compatible / available with the current DaVinci release.
ref = "default": the date of the snapshot used for the packages currently installed on DaVinci. This will help increase the chances of a successful install.
The {brave} package was developed by the SOS team to do most of the heavy lifting for you. It will download and install the package in a temporary folder, it will execute various checks, and perform the risk assessment.

This generates evidence in the form of various files that you may use to demonstrate that the package works as intended. It also creates an adhocRequire.rds file, which you need later.

ImportantadhocRequire.rds
You will need to add the generated adhocRequire.rds to source control as it contains the repository snapshot date used to install the package.

This will ensure that when your colleagues call the adhocRequire() the package gets installed from the same date as you did, ensuring reproducibility.

