Understanding brave results
{brave} installs the package and its unit tests. It will then attempt to run them as well as the vignettes and examples that are part of the package. The outcome of these assessments is both printed to the console and stored in a .zip file. Ideally, you will see something akin to this:

{mmrm} initial risk assessment: medium
Package 'mmrm' installed with PPPM snapshot '2023-03-06'
Test results (TRUE=success):
  examples tests vignettes
1     TRUE  TRUE      TRUE
tests ran on platform: x86_64-pc-linux-gnu
using R version: R version 4.1.0 (2021-05-18)
see zip file '/home/doyleor1/R-4.1.0-mmrm-2023-03-06.zip' 
Review results and assess project impact

If one of the checks (examples, tests, vignettes) is negative (has a FALSE somewhere), the important piece is to understand the reason why it failed. Some errors are acceptable or benign, but others may negatively affect the package’s performance; search the information stored in the .zip file to ascertain the root cause of the problem. If you have a negative outcome and cannot make sense of it, reach out to the SOS team to discuss options and your next steps.

Understanding the Risk Profile
The risk assessment outcome is both printed out (see above) and produces a .docx file with name <status>-<package>-riskAssessment.docx. The status is one out of five possible alternatives as described here and users are required to follow the actions (if any) that have been outlined. Note that low and medium risk no further action is needed but for other outcomes further effort is required. Reach out to the SOS team if your risk is high, undetermined or ineligible.

Using the Package
To load the package add the following code to your R program that you want to run to generate your outputs. This R program should be co-located with the adhocRequire.rds file generated during the install process.

# Add these lines of code to your R program that will use the newly installed package
library(brave)

# load the package using the "pinned" setting which reads the 
# snapshot date from the `adhocRequire.rds` file
brave::adhocRequire("<package>", ref= "pinned") 

CautionHotfix for brave if using R-4.1.0 (R-bundle-Novartis/0.6-gomkl-2019a-R-4.1.0)
You should now be able to call functions from your newly installed packaged and you can treat this package in the same manner as those pre-installed on DaVinci, i.e. as a validated package.

Storing the Evidence
The collected evidence should be stored in a version-controlled location somewhere close to the final code that uses that package. For example, the study folder in GPS2 where your programs are or in the utils folder.

What to do if brave fails installing your package
Package dependencies incompatibilities
The main reason why brave could fail to install and load your package is due to package dependencies and its versions. For example, the package that you want to install, package_1, requires a version of package_2 of v2. The problem is that package_2 is already installed in DaVinci with v1, and it has already been loaded, so an error like this could appear on RStudio:

Error: package or namespace load failed for 'package_1' in loadnamespace(j <- i[[1L]], c(lib.loc, .libPaths()), versionCheck = vI[[j]]):
namespace 'package_2' v1 is already loaded, but >= v2 is required

In order to troubleshoot this, you will need to adhoc install both package_1 and package_2 with the correct versions. You can follow this steps to try to fix the problem:

Restart your RStudio R session (Session>Restart R)
Print your sessionInfo() to make sure none of the packages you are going to install are already loaded. If they are loaded, please restart your RStudio R session again.
Set your working directory to the folder were you have your programs
Select a snapshot date that has the correct version for both packages and assign it to the ref argument
Adhoc install package_2 (the dependency that causes the problem)
Make sure that the correct version of package_2 was loaded checking sessionInfo()
Adhoc install package_1
# First restart your session doing Session>Restart R
# Make sure that not package_1 or package_2 are loaded using sessionInfo()
# if they are loaded restart your session again

# Navigate to your folder and set your working directory
setwd("~/folder")

# Set a snapshot date
ref <- "2024-06-24"

# First, install the correct version of package_2 (the package dependency causing issues)
brave::adhocRequire("package_2", ref)

# Make sure that the correct version of package_2 was loaded checking sessionInfo()

# After that, you can do it for package_1, and there should be no depencies issues
brave::adhocRequire("package_1", ref)

{renv} issues
Warning
Remember that for GxP related activities, you must use packages installed in DaVinci bundles, as they have been risk-assessed and validated.

If you are using {renv} in your project, you might run into issues when using the adhoc installation using {brave} as they are not compatible. It can happen that if you are using {renv} in other project, it gets activated even if you are in a different folder/project. Some recommendations to avoid {renv}-related problems are:

Set your GxP related project folder as your working directory and restart your RStudio R session (Session>Restart R)
Use renv::deactivate() and restart your RStudio R session (Session>Restart R)
To completely remove renv from a project, call renv::deactivate(clean = TRUE). If you later want to use renv for this project, you’ll need to start from scratch with renv::init().
